<TEXT>
behind the red door on makhoul street in west 
beirut theres a watering hole where the regulars huddle to share 
a drink seek shelter from the shelling and maybe sing along to a 
sinatra tune heres what the war clientele were up to on a 
recent night 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
hunched over a beer in the backstreet 
bar the only tavern in west beirut that has stayed open throughout 
the lebanon fighting a doctor was decribing the horrors of the 
casualty ward after recent ferocious shelling 
around the lebanese doctor a veteran of more bad nights than he 
can recall in lebanons relentless bloodletting the tavern was 
filled with about 40 people drinking from habib neaimehs 
wellstocked bar during a lull in the shelling 
neaimeh has kept his bar open six nights a week during the 
fighting 
when the shelling gets heavy i turn up the music he said 
standing behind his red and black bar on a recent night these 
people are not as relaxed as they try to appear theyre drinking 
more 
the doctor works at the american university hospital once one 
of the best medical centers in the middle east now after 14 years 
of civil war its short of medicine and trained staff it has 
taken several direct hits in recent fighting 
one night 15 people were brought in he said clutching his 
beer tightly four of them were dead 
there was a baby we thought its mother was among the dead and 
we didnt know what to do with it said the doctor 
suddenly this woman appears out of nowhere as one of our 
people is trying to soothe the baby turns out its the mother 
that story had a happy ending but for thousands of other 
lebanese the last seven weeks have brought only death injury 
devastation or confinement in bunkers and basements 
nearly 300 people have been killed and nearly 1000 wounded 
since march 8 in almost nonstop battles between army commander 
gen michel aouns mainly christian forces and an alliance of 
syrian troops and druse moslem militiamen 
neaimehs coterie of customers what he calls his war 
clientele regularly make it to the backstreet through the 
darkened alleys past packs of dogs scavenging through rotting 
ratinfested garbage to the red door in makhoul street 
shortages have forced neaimeh to trim his menu to cold cuts 
cheeses and grilled steaks 
his customers flung together by the war are a bizarre group of 
people who for their own reasons have hung on in the lebanese chaos 
and the kidnappings 
as more than 150000 people have fled the city amid the carnage 
in recent weeks the backstreet has become an oasis for this 
disparate group 
there are swiss from the red cross spanish and belgians from 
the frenchbased medecins sans frontiers agency a couple of 
russians the odd bulgarian or two and some lebanese 
neaimeh is a greek orthodox christian one of several thousand 
who live in the moslem sector most are leftists with little in 
common with the maronite catholics who make up the vast majority 
of the christians trapped in their enclave in east beirut and the 
mountains and coastal strip running north 
his only waiter is a sunni moslem the others refuse to leave 
their underground shelters to go to work and the cooks a shiite 
moslem 
despite their different religious preferences theyre a tight 
team a microcosm of whats possible in lebanon if the warring 
sects and factions could only get their act together 
this night at the bar everyones having a good time letting it 
all out but theres an undercurrent of apprehension the laughter 
sometimes has a brittle edge to it 
everyone knows someone whos been killed or wounded or lost a 
relative or whose home has been hit in the bombardments theyve 
all wondered whether the next rocket or shell to fall will have 
their name on it most are skeptical things will get better and 
many are trying to leave lebanon 
as the sound system belted out frank sinatra singing new york 
new york everyone joined in the line i want to wake up in a 
city that never sleeps enjoying the irony that the shelling 
makes sleep a luxury few get in beirut at that moment the bars 
generator sputtered and gave out 
about 11 pm rockets began to arc across beiruts dividing 
green line three miles of unrelieved devastation where christians 
and moslems have faced each other from sandbagged positions and 
gutter apartment buildings for 14 years 
incoming or outgoing a young woman asked as an explosion 
thundered nearby 
incoming i think i saw the flash a young man answered 
hesitantly 
anybody got a radio someone said whats it say 
a lebanese reporter working for a western news organization 
tuned his transistor radio to the christianrun voice of lebanon 
shells hitting the christian side the reporter said its 
outgoing 
thats ok then the young man replied 
then the radio said the source of the shelling had been 
pinpointed to west beirut the young man lost his poise told 
neaimeh hed pay his tab later and left 
he knew the christian army gunners were probably at that moment 
training their 155mm howitzers on the area around the backstreet 
bar to retaliate 
</TEXT>
