<TEXT>
the surprise declaration by sudanese rebels 
of a monthlong ceasefire reprieves the khartoum governments 
beleaguered troops and boosts an international effort to save 
100000 people facing starvation 
it also raises hopes for an end to six years of civil war that 
drains 1 million a day from the coffers of one of the worlds 
poorest countries 
mondays announcement by john garang leader of the sudan 
peoples liberation army comes at the height of his greatest 
success of the war a sixmonth string of victories that has 
government forces reeling 
rebel fighters also have been intensifying pressure on the 
strategic southern capital juba its fall could have determined 
the wars outcome by forcing the government from its largest 
stronghold in the embattled south 
but at least as important the ceasefire could boost the united 
nations struggling operation to transport more than 100000 tons 
of food and supplies to the south before heavy rains start this 
month 
last year relief officials say up to 500000 southerners died 
in the fighting or from warinduced disease and famine in villages 
isolated by flooded roads and airstrips 
garang a useducated renegade army colonel said the 
unilateral truce will hold only so long as the government refrains 
from redeploying or reinforcing its troops he said it could be 
extended 
prime minister sadek mahdi welcomed the move each step taken 
by garang toward peace will be reciprocated by two steps from the 
government he said in a may day speech 
only last month garang rejected a unproposed month of 
tranquillity to allow the 132 million relief operation easy 
access to 23 million waraffected southerners 
instead he guaranteed safe conduct for specific relief convoys 
but attacks by unidentified armed groups bureaucratic hassles 
inadequate transport infrastructure and bad planning have hampered 
the operation only 37000 tons of food was delivered in april 
un officials say they will continue until the rains cut 
transport routes 
i think the overriding reasons behind this decision are 
political but they are bound to be connected with the relief 
effort said richard reid the regional director of unicef who 
conducts most un negotiations with the rebels 
were keeping our fingers crossed but it ought to help the 
operation if only by easing things and reducing the level of 
anxiety reid said in a telephone interview from amman jordan 
military experts in khartoum interpreted the rebels rejection 
of the original truce as evidence of unwillingness to impede their 
battlefield winning streak 
since then mahdi has come under army pressure and approved a 
tentative peace plan which the rebels welcomed with cautious 
optimism 
the ceasefire was the next logical step in the peace 
process said peter woodward a lecturer at englands reading 
university and a specialist on sudan who returned from khartoum 
last week 
now its up to the government to arrange for further steps 
woodward said in a telephone interview 
garangs broadcast said all his forces will remain in their 
positions to wait for the government to implement the 
requirements of the sudanese peace initiative 
a joint technical military committee then would work out a 
comprehensive ceasefire he said 
the agreements most politically sensitive clause calls for the 
suspension of harsh islamic laws in force since late 1983 the 
mainly animist and christian rebels took up arms against the 
moslemdominated government a few months earlier demanding 
autonomy for the south 
mahdi the leader of a sudanese moslem sect approved the 
suspension last month leaving the way clear for a constitutional 
conference 
in the two years that the rebels have won an upper hand in the 
war southern civilians have suffered as both sides used food as a 
weapon 
juba a city of dusty streets and thatchedroof mud huts whose 
population is swollen by refugees to five times its normal 30000 
has been besieged for more than two years rebels intensified their 
attacks these past few months 
the splas military successes created a very difficult 
political situation for them said woodward if they took over 
the major towns in the south it would mean a de facto 
separation of sudan and it would be much more difficult to try and 
negotiate a peaceful settlement for a united sudan now they 
negotiate from a position of strength 
military sources in khartoum say about 20000 troops are holed 
up in the middle of juba 
one source estimated the armys strength at 75000 and the 
rebels at 57000 but government troops are outnumbered in the war 
because only 10000 soldiers remain in major southern towns other 
than juba 
