<TEXT>
business representatives contend that american 
workers would be better off if congress repealed a new law aimed at 
barring healthinsurance discrimination against lowerpaid 
employees 
we remain skeptical that it does anything to improve or extend 
coverage of health care james h gardner a californian speaking 
for the national federation of independent business told the house 
ways and means committee tuesday 
gardner said house legislation to revise the law would be an 
improvement but that the best course would be outright repeal 
it will still be a new impediment and disincentive to 
employers especially smaller employers to provide health 
insurance gardner said 
similar objections were raised by other business representatives 
who testified before the tax panel but spokesmen for the treasury 
department the aflcio and the accounting profession leaned toward 
revising the law known as internal revenue code section 89 rather 
than repealing it 
prompt congressional action is needed to alleviate the 
problems employers are experiencing in complying with section 89 
said dana l trier tax legislative counsel for the treasury 
department we believe the revision bill represents a major 
step forward in achieving these goals 
he said treasury advocates a complete revision of present law 
which he called a complicated mess 
the law enacted in 1986 aims to ensure that taxdeductible 
health insurance plans do not discriminate in favor of higherpaid 
employees the statute requires employers to subject their health 
plans to complex tests to determine whether they discriminate 
some employers say the complexity paperwork and cost 50 per 
worker by one estimate are so onerous that they will find it 
easier to drop their health plans rather than try to comply with 
the law 
business has made repeal or modification of the law a major goal 
this year congress has heard so many complaints that 300 house 
members and close to a majority of the senate have signed bills to 
repeal the law most members of the ways and means committee have 
signed the revision bill whose chief sponsor is chairman dan 
rostenkowski dill 
the complaints have been heard by the bush administration too 
treasury secretary nicholas brady announced monday that employers 
would not have to test their health plans for compliance before 
oct 1 the law originally had a jan 1 1989 deadline 
the federal government forgoes more than 30 billion a year in 
taxes on the value of employerfinanced health coverage 
rostenkowskis bill would eliminate most of the complicated 
testing by requiring employers to provide to at least 90 percent of 
their lowerpaid workers health insurance costing the employees no 
more than 10 a month for a single plan or no more than 25 for 
family coverage 
calvin johnson legislative representative for the aflcio 
praised rostenkowskis bill but said the labor federation questions 
whether it would make it possible for working families to qualify 
for coverage he recommended that a workers outofpocket spending 
for medical expenses be limited to 3000 a year and that the 
25aweek maximum premium under the bill be reduced 
the committee was asked to provide special exemptions for state 
and local governments since such employers pay no federal taxes 
and thus receive no tax deduction for the costs of workers 
insurance 
lee cooke mayor of austin texas speaking for the national 
league of cities said at least 27 states require workers to pay 
more than 10 a week for a single health policy or more than 25 
weekly for a family plan 
overall cooke said while congressional concern about the 
30billionayear subsidy for health plans is understandable we 
believe that the burdens of the law far outweigh the benefits in 
the public sector 
