<TEXT>
when president bush travels to new york he 
gets there quicker than george washington but slower than ronald 
reagan 
thats because bush has eliminated one link in the trip used by 
reagan a fast helicopter ride into manhattan from a nearby 
airport usually newark 
instead bush prefers to travel within new york by motorcade 
and that means he must land at the most distant of new yorks 
three major airports kennedy 
closerin laguardia wont accommodate air force one a boeing 
707 and he cant use newark across the hudson river in new 
jersey for security and national defense reasons 
a motorcade trip from newark would require the presidents 
motorcade to pass through a tunnel under the river and that would 
put the chief executive out of radio contact with the rest of the 
world unless special communications cables were laid through the 
tunnel deemed by the white house not worth the expense or effort 
so bush who has been to new york twice as president travels 
through the nations most populous city entirely by motorcade 
producing monumental traffic tieups as he goes 
for last sundays trip when bush participated in a reenactment 
of washingtons inauguration 200 years before bush traveled by 
motorcade all the way from kennedy international airport on long 
island to wall street in lower manhattan a trip of about 35 
minutes 
bushs decision not to use a helicopter to get into new york was 
based on his preference to save money said spokesman stephen 
hart 
at a time when were facing budgetary constraints its one 
way he could have an impact hart said 
hart said it was not clear how much was really saved by such a 
step however 
usually four helicopters were involved when reagan traveled 
from newark airport into manhattan usually to a helipad at the 
battery one helicopter for the president and his top aides one 
for the secret service another for lesserranking staff and a 
press chopper 
at least some of the helicopters had to be flown up from 
washington 
however official motorcades through new york are to say it 
mildly interesting 
they are sometimes chaotic hectic frightening exhilarating 
and always gridlockforming 
as president bush gets streets barricaded for him along the 
motorcade route that presents an unusual sight to anyone familiar 
with new yorks usually clogged streets block after block of 
temporarily empty pavement 
of course side streets and entrance ramps along the way become 
hopelessly clogged with stopped traffic 
as vice president and as a candidate bush didnt always rate 
such treatment and his new york motorcades often had to vie with 
and fend off other traffic 
sirens and flashing lights seem to have less effect on traffic 
in new york than in other cities cars buses and cabs frequently 
dart in and out of the path of nonpresidential motorcades 
when a motorcade slows down too much or too much of a gap opens 
between cars pedestrians and bicyclists often stream perilously 
across the street between the gaps 
during a campaign visit last spring a vehicle in thenvice 
president bushs motorcade struck a cab trying to edge into the 
flow of traffic crumpling its side the motorcade kept moving the 
cab driver shaking his fist and hurling epithets 
new york motorcades usually produce a higher percentage of 
hand and finger gestures asserts one white house staff member 
is saving the cost of helicopters worth the added cost of more 
police officers along motorcade routes and the jangled nerves of 
those caught in traffic jams 
you have to try to strike a balance said bush spokesman 
hart 
and he noted reagan only took choppers from the airport into 
the city he still had to travel by motorcade within manhattan 
although it takes bush longer than reagan to get to a new york 
site hes still a lot swifter than the nations first president 
whose steps bush retraced last sunday 
it took washington a week in 1789 to travel from mount vernon 
in virginia near what is now the nations capital to new york 
which was then the nations capital and he did it by horseback 
coach and barge 
</TEXT>
