<TEXT>
a bill that would give airlines and airports 
270 million for devices to detect plastic explosives goes before a 
house committee thursday after a subcommittee rejected republican 
efforts to make airlines pay half the cost 
the legislation requires installation of the sophisticated units 
in us and foreign airports that are considered vulnerable to 
terrorists it does the same thing as a transportation department 
order last month which would have airlines pay the full cost of 
the units 
the bill passed tuesday by the house public works aviation 
subcommittee would take the 270 million from an aviation trust 
fund without budgeting new money the fund has accumulated more 
than 6 billion in fees collected from airline passengers for 
airport improvements 
republicans tried to amend the measure to require that us 
airlines pay half the cost but the bill received no opposing votes 
when it passed with full federal funding for the security devices 
the transportation department last month ordered airlines to 
install the sophisticated bombdetection machines at highrisk 
airports both the order and the legislation call for detection 
systems such as thermal neutron devices that have been tested by 
the federal aviation administration 
transportation secretary samuel skinner said tuesday he expects 
the first machine to be installed in july at john f kennedy 
international airport in new york and the second at an airport in 
great britain he said several more should be in place before the 
end of the year 
skinner was in europe last week meeting with officials of other 
governments about aviation security as a result of the dec 21 
bombing of pan am flight 103 over scotland that killed 270 people 
he said the administration feels the airlines should pay for 
additional security using revenue from security fees collected 
with passengers tickets 
the legislation would provide up to 100 percent grants to us 
airlines and airports which would own operate and maintain the 
detection units expected to cost about 1 million each the airline 
grants also would cover installation in highrisk foreign airports 
subcommittee chairman rep james oberstar dminn argued that 
the government should pay for the devices that would examine 
checkedin baggage because the government not airlines has been 
the target of terrorists 
other governments will be paying for security units used by 
their airlines which would put them at a competitive advantage 
oberstar said 
republicans argued that airlines have always paid for security 
equipment at airports and the subsidy could lead to other moves to 
use federal money to help airlines 
