to curb inflation 
still there were signs in wednesdays report that wage gains 
are not outpacing inflation in general 
the labor department reported that hourly compensation in 
nonfarm business rose 57 percent in the first quarter but real 
hourly compensation which takes into account the increase in 
consumer prices in that period grew by only 03 percent for all 
of 1988 hourly compensation adjusted to factor in consumer 
inflation rose a revised 04 percent the department said 
in manufacturing real hourly compensation lagged 06 percent 
behind inflation in 1988 and 12 percent behind in the first 
quarter compared to the fourth quarter of 1988 according to the 
government data 
in a separate gauge the government reported that unit labor 
costs obtained by dividing compensation by output rose 52 
percent in the first quarter from the previous three months and 49 
percent compared to the first quarter of 1988 
the improved productivity in manufacturing in the first quarter 
included a gain of 36 percent for durable goods and 4 percent for 
nondurables 
the report included revised productivity data for 1988 with the 
government reporting overall nonfarm productivity improved 15 
percent over the year as output increased 52 percent while total 
hours worked grew 37 percent 
the government reported overall business productivity 
including farming increased at a 35 percent annual rate in the 
first quarter but that figure is heavily influenced by the 
agricultural rebound after last years drought productivity had 
declined 1 percent in the overall business category in the final 
quarter of 1988 
