the town of rantoul ill is the first to 
receive a federal planning grant from the pentagon to help cope 
with the upcoming round of military base closings the defense 
department said wednesday 
the community located next to the chanute air force base will 
receive 73045 to help organize a base reuse committee to start 
planning the civilian conversion of the base property according 
to a pentagon statement 
in addition to the federal money rantoul is contributing money 
and services worth 11300 and the state of illinois 10000 to 
support the effort 
the reuse committee will oversee development of a balanced 
plan for the property covering such uses as aviation industrial 
development housing education recreation and possibly 
healthrelated activities the pentagon statement said 
the grant was made by the pentagons office of economic 
adjustment which has helped more than 400 communities since 1961 
deal with the closure of nearby military facilities 
the grant to rantoul however is the first since congress 
approved a long list of base closings last month under a special 
procedure set up last year chanute air force base is one of 86 
bases now set for closure under the program which was prompted 
primarily by budget concerns 
savings from the plan which also includes substantial changes 
at 54 other facilities are estimated at 694 million a year at 
first savings over 20 years are estimated at 56 billion 
the pentagon has estimated that 15 to 20 communities will apply 
for grants similar to that given rantoul besides planning grants 
the pentagon office also is authorized to help with the 
construction or hardware costs of converting bases to other uses 
the department has asked congress for 2 million in fiscal 1990 
for economic adjustment work 
