<TEXT>
the chairman of a house subcommittee 
criticized the environmental protection agency wednesday for not 
doing more to stop pesticides banned in this country from showing 
up in imported food 
the government must ensure that foreign buyers of usmade 
pesticides understand their dangers and protect the american public 
from imported food contaminated with unsafe pesticides said rep 
mike synar dokla 
the epa has failed miserably said synar chairman of the 
house government operations committees subcommittee on 
environment energy and natural resources which has jurisdiction 
over the agency 
during a hearing of his subcommittee synar said agriculture 
department inspectors found chlordane a chemical believed to cause 
cancer in two shipments of honduran beef 
our reports show that chlordane is made only in the united 
states but is not allowed to be sold here as pesticide said 
synar 
in both cases most of the honduran beef had been sold to 
grocery stores ground up and purchased by consumers before the 
chlordane contamination was discovered 
synar criticized the epa for not warning the agriculture 
department that honduras was buying an americanmade pesticide that 
could contaminate beef sold to the united states 
its time for congress to revisit our pesticide export 
policies he said 
during the hearing epa officials admitted they cant ensure 
that pesticides outlawed here wont show up in imported food but 
they also charged that the subcommittee hasnt followed its own 
suggestions for helping other countries better understand the 
dangers of some pesticides made in the us 
linda fisher epa assistant administrator for policy planning 
and evaluation said the agency was aware more needed to be done 
when presented with an internal memo dated april 17 1987 that 
outlined improvements needed to better educate foreign buyers and 
protect american consumers she conceded that none had been 
followed 
but fisher assured synar the epa would quickly act on the 
recommendations as well as those of international negotiators 
working to establish a policy for worldwide pesticide use 
synars charges against the epa were supported by a report from 
the general accounting office an investigative arm of congress 
the gao said epa has no established procedures for deciding when 
to notify foreign countries about pesticides the united states has 
designated dangerous to human health 
the epa also has no standards for determining whether action 
taken against pesticides in this country are significant enough to 
warn another nation according to the gao report 
under us law pesticides that are banned or unregistered 
domestically can be sold abroad if the foreign buyer provides a 
statement saying he understands that the product is outlawed in the 
united states a copy of that statement is provided to the foreign 
government through the state department 
the epa does not routinely send out notices to foreign 
governments when companies voluntarily cancel domestic 
registrations the gao said 
the agency is considering improvements to its present 
procedures including those reocmmended by gao said fisher 
</TEXT>
