<DOCNO> AP890503-0184 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
stiff prison sentences are fine the 
administrations top drugcontrol official said wednesday but in 
drug cases certainty of punishment is more important than 
severity 
william j bennett director of the office of national drug 
control policy told several hundred members of the washington 
metropolitan area interreligious coalition that his approach to the 
drug problem can be summed up in the words consequences and 
confrontation 
those who use sell and traffic in drugs must be confronted 
and they must suffer consequences bennett said he is working on 
a strategy for drug control nationwide with a report due in early 
september 
while saying there is broad agreement on such consequences as 
seizure of assets stiffer prison sentences revocation of bail 
rights and the death penalty for drug kingpins he added i 
also find that we lack the resources to assure that consequences 
always follow crime 
he called for more prisons and jails and for more investigators 
prosecutors and judges but also said more and tougher action 
will not be enough 
i think we need to reorient our process of justice where drugs 
are concerned and adopt the principle that certainty of punishment 
is more important than severity of punishment bennett said 
those guilty of drug offenses must believe that punishment is 
inevitable as long as they dont the deterrent effect of 
incarceration is neutralized 
after the speech bennett said he wasnt suggesting reduced 
sentences for drug offenders including what he termed casual users 
i am for severe penalties particularly when a drug crime is 
severe but what you have to have is certain punishment he said 
you shouldnt make certain punishment hostage to severe 
punishment 
what that means is a person that commits a drug crime has to 
know theyre going to be punished and if you have to sacrifice an 
extra six months of punishment in order to be sure the person gets 
some punishment make sure they get some punishment bennett 
said it would be better in many situations to have everyone 
thats convicted of drug use to go to jail for a week than to 
just get a third of them going for six months 
as an example he cited a practice in phoenix where he said 
police arrested drug users many of them middleclass and put 
them in jail for a weekend thats all just a weekend for a lot 
of middleclass users that is plenty of time they are cured 
after one weekend in the slammer 
bennett acknowledged that such an idea would be for state and 
local governments to carry out and that he as director of national 
drug control policy would not be imposing such regulations on the 
federal level 
but he said local officials have asked him repeatedly during his 
two months on the job to let them know if there are any good ideas 
floating around and the phoenix example is one hes advocating 
another local example he touted was that of toledo ohio where 
parents are brought before the juvenile justice court and made to 
answer for the actions of their children through civil penalties 
this policy establishes the principle that parents must 
bear responsibility for the behavior and the activities of minors 
in their charge bennett said minors who are nonaddicted 
users must be taught early on that they cannot behave with 
impunity and parents who have effectively turned them loose must 
learn why the social contract demands that they oversee and control 
the impulses of their children 
asked later if that included jailing parents for their 
childrens transgressions bennett said that should occur only in 
extreme cases 
as for treatment and rehabilitation of drug offenders bennett 
told the coalition that in many cases rehabilitation is the 
wrong term to use 
in the case of 15yearold offenders who have grown up 
essentially without parents some therapists i have talked to have 
found it necessary to serve as substitute parents complete with a 
tuckin and bedtime story at night he said 
</TEXT>
