<TEXT>
congress was asked wednesday to set up a 60 
million soybean research and promotion program financed by a levy 
on domestic soybean production 
proposed legislation developed by the american soybean 
association would provide for a nationwide checkoff similar to 
programs involving other commodities including those for dairy 
pork and beef producers 
money from a mandatory assessment would pay for farmerrun 
programs to expand exports develop new uses for soybeans and 
promote soybean products through a national advertising campaign 
the program would be administered by state and national boards 
composed of soybean producers 
this program is and will be farmerbred farmerfed and 
farmerled said james lee adams of camilla ga president of 
the american soybean association 
at a news conference sen david pryor dark said the 
legislation would give american soybean farmers a war chest of 
their own to combat promotional and research efforts of foreign 
competitors 
currently 26 states have soybean promotion programs generating 
a total of about 15 million and the national levy would replace 
those 
the proposed rate of assessment would be onehalf percent of the 
net market value of soybeans sold by a farmer 50 cents for every 
100 in sales half of the estimated 60 million in collections 
would go to state programs 
if the legislation is enacted the assessment would be 
implemented and a producer referendum would be held 18 to 36 months 
later to determine whether it should continue 
