<TEXT>
warring factions agreed wednesday to 
implement a ceasefire plan to end the beirut bloodbath that has 
killed 278 people in eight weeks an arab league peacemaker 
announced 
there is no justification for a single shot to be fired in 
lebanon as of now algerian diplomat lakhdar ibrahimi told 
reporters after meeting separately with lebanons rival cabinet 
leaders sunni moslem salim hoss and christian gen michel aoun 
several hours after ibrahimis announcement however police 
reported a new violation of the truce 
as speedboats began ferrying passengers from the harbor of the 
christian port of jounieh to the cypriotflagged ferry baroness m 
anchored 15 miles off the coast three shells fired from 
syrianpoliced west beirut crashed on the byblos coast nine miles 
north of jounieh police said 
they said the captain of the baroness m refused to enter the 
port 12 miles north of beirut because he was skeptical about 
guarantees that his vessel would not be shelled 
a police spokesman who spoke on condition of anonymity 
according to regulations said the violation did not interrupt the 
transport of about 500 passengers onto the baroness m to be ferried 
to the cypriot port of larnaca 
the ship and another boat the larnaca rose had evacuated about 
15000 people from the christian enclave during the fighting but 
both suspended the shuttles april 24 after they became the target 
of syrian and druse moslem gunners 
earlier police reported some sniper fire from moslem west 
beirut into the christian sector but a spokesman played down the 
violation and said it seems the ceasefire orders havent been 
issued yet no casualties were reported 
aouns 20000 lebanese army soldiers have battled moslem 
militiamen and allied syrian soldiers since march 3 more than 
1000 people have been injured in that time 
ibrahimi and kuwaits ambassador to syria abdelaziz jassem 
arrived in beirut earlier wednesday seeking to enforce an arab 
leaguebrokered truce that began april 28 
it scaled down indiscriminate bombardment of population centers 
in and around beirut but it was violated repeatedly after three 
days because aoun rejected the second clause of the accord 
refusing to lift a blockade of three illegal militiarun ports 
the blockade through which aoun wanted to restore government 
authority and gather taxes worth 100 million a year ignited the 
latest fighting 
druse and syrian gunners who outnumber christian forces by 31 
retaliated by firing at christian ports then besieged the 
christian heartland and trapped some 1 million christians in a 
310squaremile enclave 
ibrahimi said aoun now has accepted to implement the decision 
adopted by the arab foreign ministers which calls for lifting all 
blockades imposed on all air and sea ports 
beirut airport the countrys only international air transport 
facility was closed by christian shellfire march 12 
ibrahimi said aoun also agreed to reopen road crossings that 
link beiruts moslem and christian sectors for three months while 
the arab league brokers a comprehensive settlement 
i can say the ceasefire has taken effect today after the 
settlement of the ports dispute the observer force will begin 
arriving soon ibrahimi said but did not give a date 
an aide to hoss said ibrahimi proposed deploying arab observers 
at the disputed ports where aoun has charged militias also run 
guns and drugs aoun agreed to the envoys compromise 
kuwaiti foreign minister sheik sabah ahmed who heads the arab 
league panel on lebanon stressed wednesday that the observers will 
be sent only after the ceasefire is consolidated 
we are not prepared to sacrifice any arab brethren in the 
continued shelling and exchange of fire he told the kuwait news 
agency 
aoun has welcomed the deployment of an arab observer team 
saying it also would monitor the 40000 syrian soldiers in lebanon 
whom christians accuse of breaking a 1976 arab league peacekeeping 
mandate by siding with the moslems 
the observers presence is expected to loosen syrias grip as 
lebanons sole powerbroker 
