<DOCNO> AP890503-0229 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
an african rebel leader urged the united 
states on wednesday to help end the protracted war between the 
strategically placed province of eritrea and the sovietbacked 
government of ethiopia 
isaias afwerki secretary general of the eritrean peoples 
liberation front said he hoped to convey his views to us 
officials and lawmakers although he declined to say whom he would 
be meeting 
state department officials who said afwerki is the most senior 
eritrean rebel leader ever to visit here also declined to say 
whether they would meet with him 
afwerki said he did not have any specific initiatives to offer 
but hoped the united states would contribute to a lasting 
solution for the conflict by helping bring the sides to the 
negotiating table 
us policy rejects eritreas demands for secession from 
ethiopia advocating negotiations between the sides to end what has 
become at 27 years africas longest war 
state department officials have occasionally met with members of 
the eplf the largest of several eritrean groups the us also 
maintains ties with the government of ethiopian military chairman 
mengistu haile mariam although relations have deteriorated since 
ethiopia switched allegiance to the soviet union in 1977 
afwerkis visit comes at a time when mengistu suffering 
economic woes and military defeats to the rebels is also making 
overtures to the us administration 
ethiopias prospects are bleaker than ever afwerki 
contended at a seminar sponsored by the center for strategic and 
international studies an independent think tank the eplf which 
is backed by several arab governments but relies mostly on captured 
soviet weaponry has claimed significant military victories over 
the past year 
us officials believe the organization controls about 75 
percent of eritrea which overlooks a key water route to the oil 
fields of saudi arabia but that the government retains control of 
the provinces major ports and cities officials here say the 
government is also under pressure from its main arms supplier the 
soviet union to end the costly war 
afwerki said the soviet union despite claims to the contrary 
continues to arm the ethiopian government 
nonetheless the eplf is among the first who hope to benefit 
from recent cooperation between the us and the soviet union in 
resolving regional conflicts around the world afwerki said such 
superpower cooperation as evidenced by agreements ending the 
soviet occupation of afghanistan and the cuban occupation of 
angola has made his organization optimistic about prospects for 
negotiations with ethiopia 
the eplf is still holding out for its 1980 proposal to conduct a 
referendum that would determine whether eritrea remains an 
autonomous part of ethiopia or secedes from it altogether he said 
the eplf has in the past proposed thirdcountry mediation to end 
the war with ethiopia but has spurned proposals for italy or sudan 
to bring the sides together 
afwerki rejected claims that his group is marxist in nature 
calling that a pretext for past us indifference and said the 
eplf represented varying economic views and was committed to a free 
economy 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

