<DOCNO> AP890503-0245 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
among the many financial innovations of the 
1980s few have achieved as much broad popularity as the 
homeequity loan 
it isnt hard to understand why homeequity loans serve as a 
convenient way to tap one of the nations greatest pools of wealth 
on top of that changes in the laws have given them a special 
tax status in contrast to most other types of consumer borrowing 
interest paid on the typical homeequity loan remains fully 
deductible within specified limits 
but with all their advantages homeequity loans also carry with 
them more potential risks and drawbacks than many people realize 
financial advisers say 
as albert ellentuck at the accounting firm of laventhol amp 
horwath puts it homeequity loan agreements like cigarette 
packages should carry a consumer warning in large type caution 
this loan could be hazardous to your financial health 
the biggest pitfall in homeequity borrowing the risk of 
losing your house if you cant keep up with payments has been 
widely publicized and deservedly so 
this point alone makes a powerful case against using homeequity 
credit for any frivolous or shortterm purpose such as a vacation 
or a shopping spree 
ideally the money borrowed should finance an asset with a vaue 
at least as great as the total cost of the loan and expected to 
last at least as long as the term of the loan 
the most obvious example of this kind of asset would be 
improvements to the property itself 
say you take out a 10year home equity loan to finance a new 
car ellentuck observes 
the car is gone long before youve paid off your loan by 
stretching the debt over so long a period youre just racking up 
huge interest charges 
this may seem to be plain common sense but ellentuck points out 
that there are some other possible perils with homeequity loans 
that arent so readily apparent 
homeequity credit often is touted as an inexpensive way to 
borrow since lenders generally charge lower interest rates on 
loans backed by such solid collateral 
although that may be true in principle ellentuck says 
appraisal costs other upfront charges and annual account fees 
make some equity loans a lot more costly than the stated interest 
rate suggests 
watch out in particular he counsels for deals with 
bargainbasement teaser interest rates that can be raised 
sharply just a few months after the loan is made 
in many homeequity deals borrowers are allowed to pay only 
interest charges for a period of time without repaying any of the 
principal 
whatever advantages that may afford ellentuck points out it 
makes a loan more expensive than a conventional arrangement in 
which payments cover both interest and part of the principal 
thats because the balance due remains at its original high level 
furthermore such a setup typically leaves you faced with a 
balloon payment at the end of the loans term which may or may 
not be easy to finance at that time 
if youre seriously considering a home equity loan shop 
around ellentuck concludes 
look for a loan that imposes no points on closing offers a 
low cap on the increase in your variable interest rate and charges 
annual fees of 20 or less 
end advance pm thurs may 4 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0246 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
one reason why americans save so little is the 
bomb said the professor if theres no tomorrow that is youll 
just be a gone fool 
this is the latest contribution to the literature of why 
americans dont save more of their income it is now a massive 
collection and growing no academic can retain his reputation 
without taking a stab at the problem 
the bomb thesis has been developed by joel b slemrod of the 
university of michigan based on his studies of 20 noncommunist 
nations the lowsaving american registers the highest level of 
fear of nuclear war 
in 1986 he explains 49 percent of his american respondents 
felt there was an even or betterthaneven chance of a nuclear 
war within 10 years at the same time the us savings rate was 
19th only frances rate was lower 
in japan on the other hand only 15 percent of those surveyed 
in the same year believed the chance of nuclear war within a decade 
was 50 percent or better japans savings rate was bettered only by 
italy and luxembourg 
slemrod believes the evidence might compel a lot of economists 
to revise their views of why americans save relatively little in 
the past he says a lot of people have been blaming it on taxes 
and the social security system 
and you might add on dozens of other things on demographics 
for example a surge of 25to34yearolds has been coursing 
through the economy they must buy furniture houses cars 
childrens clothing and such with money that otherwise might have 
been put into savings 
according to the theory as these yuppies become older theyll 
transmogrify into couch potatoes they will sit before their 
television sets content not to keep buying and traveling they 
will save and invest for the future 
thats just one notion among the others is that the methodology 
by which savings statistics are amassed is faulty as some explain 
it americans use their houses as banks but the statisticians 
dont count that as saving 
social security and private pension plans have been blamed they 
make americans complacent about their futures it is said although 
that notion is receiving a severe jolt from the actual painful 
experiences of retirees 
there is no end to the possibilities that have been seriously 
studied at academic institutions analyzed by elected officials and 
speculated on by economists but there are also some very obvious 
reasons that require no study 
such as 
in america savings are taxed it used to be even worse 
savings were taxed while debt earned the borrower a great tax 
deduction in regard to housing debt it remains so even credit 
card debt still gets a small deduction the tax system in many 
other countries encourages saving even exempting some earned 
interest from the tax collector 
that idea caught on strongly in the united states a decade or so 
ago with individual retirement accounts but iras have since been 
weakened taxes on interest earnings are deferred but no longer is 
there a tax deduction 
in the united states keeping up with the joneses is a much 
derided but much practiced philosophy of life this is a consumer 
society not a saver society 
if you dont think so examine the basic theme of many 
advertisements if your neighbor has something why dont you 
arent you as good in every way as your neighbor then demonstrate 
it 
consider some of the other themes one car is not enough 
neither is one bath in your house in fact one house isnt enough 
good heavens what do you do on weekends 
save banks are for saving arent they maybe not as you might 
conclude from examining the literature you receive from them how 
many seek to have you save with them how many offer you credit 
instead 
the us personal savings rate rarely exceeds 6 percent 
compared with 20 percent or so in japan it is indeed puzzling and 
social scientists will question each other about it for many 
academic years 
the answer however is far more likely to come directly from 
the source from the american consumer who may indeed save little 
because of the bomb but who also might be borrowing more for the 
same reason 
