<DOCNO> AP890503-0307 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the eec commission wednesday released 
its 1989 report on us trade barriers singling out 42 regulations 
and trade practices that it said impedes imports from the 12 
european economic community nations 
the barriers include quantitative restrictions export 
subsidies customs barriers public procurement policies 
countervailing duties antidumping procedures and tax policies 
the eec report said 
its release came five days after the us administration 
released its report on foreign trade practices it considers unfair 
eec commission spokesman claus ehlermann said the timing of the 
release of the eec report was not linked to the us report he 
said the eec report was an annual event and its release simply 
coincided with the report by the office of the us special 
trade representative 
the eec report criticized the 1988 us fair trade practices act 
which it said will make it more likely that unilateral action 
will be taken to redress allegedly unfair trade practices 
such unilateral actionwithout authorization from the 
general agreement on tariffs and trade is illegal 
the report also cited the buy american provision of the us 
trade act that has created permanent discrimination in favor of 
us products 
the clause provides for action by the us administration 
against foreign countries which discriminate against us products 
or services in government procurement including a ban against 
offending countries 
another category of restrictions includes us measures which 
have been found to violate international trading rules and in 
which the united states has neither modified nor offered 
compensation to its trade partners for trade damage caused 
as examples the report cites the us failure to implement 
findings of the gatt on the illegality of the superfund oil 
levy and the nonconformity of the us system of customs 
users fees 
</TEXT>
