<DOCNO> AP890503-0311 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
president bushs plan to rescue the sampl 
industry faces potential challenges from two powerful house 
committee chairmen after receiving a strong vote of support from 
the banking panel 
the house banking committee capped four days of debate by 
approving the plan on a 492 vote tuesday minutes before midnight 
the senate had passed its own version of the bill last week 
the legislation provides 157 billion over the next decade most 
of it from taxpayers to close or merge more than 500 failed 
institutions 
it also would put sampl regulators under more direct 
administration control increase spending to uncover fraud at sampls 
and in the key reform require sampl owners to risk more of their 
own capital when they make loans 
the bush administration is particularly pleased with the house 
bills capital provisions and is calling for congress to swiftly 
complete the legislative process and put a finished bill on the 
presidents desk 
the risk now is delay said assistant treasury secretary 
david w mullins one of the architects of the bush plan the bill 
has gone through so far without major changes if someone 
wanted to tinker with major components we would argue that would 
be unwarranted and very costly 
in a statement treasury secretary nicholas brady indicated the 
administration would be working to modify some provisions of the 
bill passed by the house banking committee before the measure 
clears congress 
brady singled out changes in the administrations proposals for 
setting up the resolution trust corp a new federal agency to 
dispose of repossessed assets of insolvent sampls including a 
provision which would require that some of the property be sold to 
lowincome people at a discount 
we do have serious concerns about the nature and direction of 
amendments which reconfigure the resoution trust corp the 
committee has made substantial modifications which alter the 
original design and intent of the administration proposal brady 
said we are particularly concerned about provisions that would 
divert resources needed for savings and loan resolutions to housing 
subsidies 
staff aides to the banking committee are expected to take until 
the end of next week to put the panels bill in proper form and 
write a report accompanying the legislation other committees with 
an interest in parts of the measure would then get a week to 
produce alternatives leaving a slim chance that the full house 
would before memorial day 
administration officials are also happy that both the senate and 
house so far have stuck with bushs complicated mechanism for 
keeping 50 billion in sampl spending out of the budget deficit 
however both rep dan rostenkowski dill the house ways and 
means committee chairman and rep claude pepper dfla the 
chairman of the rules committee disagree with major provisions of 
the bill 
rostenkowski in a speech last month said he believes the bush 
financing mechanism wastes about 150 million a year because it 
inflates the governments borrowing costs 
hes being urged by rep charles schumer dny a member of 
the banking committee to pursue the issue by including the sampl 
spending in the budget deficit but exempting it from the automatic 
cuts under grammrudman 
if nothing else rostenkowski can push it and back off and 
collect a few chits from the administration said an industry 
lobbyist who spoke on condition of anonymity hes got absolutely 
nothing to lose it makes him a player on a very important issue 
pepper whose panel governs debate on the house floor is 
pushing for looser capital rules arguing that it is unfair to take 
away accounting breaks given to sampls in the early 1980s in exchange 
for their takeover of ailing institutions 
the legislation requires sampl owners to risk 3 of real money 
or tangible capital for every 100 they lend double the 
requirement of the bill passed by the senate last month the 
capital would act as a buffer to absorb losses before government 
deposit insurance kicks in 
pepper is likely to insist that the full house get a chance to 
reconsider the capital provisions 
</TEXT>
