<TEXT>
corporate directors will be able to use a 
poison pill to ward off unwanted takeover bids in new york 
under a bill signed into law wednesday by gov mario cuomo 
companies in other states can enact a poison pill or 
antitakeover plan on their own but legislation was needed in new 
york because of a court decision last year that barred companies 
from treating the shares of a wouldbe acquirer different from 
those of other shareholders 
the state had given that power to directors but it expired 
april 1 
the new law gives boards of directors facing a hostile takeover 
a chance to buy time to evaluate and react to the offers by using 
a poison pill those directors could make it more expensive for an 
outsider to buy a controlling portion of stock 
at the same time most poison pills allow stockholders of the 
company to buy more shares at a cheaper price 
the new law takes effect immediately and expires july 1 between 
now and then cuomo and the legislature are expected to work on 
some sort of permanent poison pill measure 
poison pills generally have been supported by management and 
fortune 500 companies while they largely have been opposed by the 
securities industry and takeover entrepreneurs 
passage of this bill removes an incentive for people to leave 
new york said robert ward spokesman for the business council 
the states largest business lobbying group 
the bill was approved unanimously in the democraticcontrolled 
state assembly earlier wednesday 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

