<TEXT>
an illinois wastedisposal company 
shipped a barge containing toxic levels of lead and cadmium 
overseas without required government approval and the us 
government has proposed a 51750 fine 
triangle metallurgical inc of granite city which failed to get 
spains permission to export the material is the first company hit 
with a fine under 1986 hazardouswaste export laws the st louis 
postdispatch reported wednesday 
us epa is committed to ensuring that this countrys 
hazardous waste problems are not simply relocated to other 
countries said epa regional administrator valdus v adamkus who 
also proposed a 12700 fine against beelman truck co of st 
libory which is accused of accepting the shipment without proper 
documentation 
the triangle shipment to spain was one of thousands last year by 
businesses seeking to avoid the expense of complying with us 
hazardouswaste laws the postdispatch reported 
but for triangle the matter did not end when the ship 
containing its wastes docked this year in bilbao spain 
under us law toxicwaste exporters must notify the epa and 
working through the state department gain approval from the 
importing nation before shipment 
in triangles case the company notified the epa but the ship 
set sail before spanish approval was granted the postdispatch 
said 
triangle president william t wegryzn acknowledged the materials 
were not shipped with spains approval but said he believed 
notifying the epa was sufficient 
the materials were not highly toxic chemical wastes said 
officials of the company which takes metal wastes from steel 
mills foundries and smelters and then resells them 
on dec 28 about 750 cubic yards of metal waste and 
contaminated dirt from a 1984 triangle warehouse fire was trucked 
to a barge on the mississippi river and sent to europe the 
newspaper said 
the ship containing the waste arrived in bilbao spain on feb 
11 and the waste was trucked to er cosa a company that reclaims 
copper 
er cosa official jose antonio boveda said government approval 
was not required in spain to receive the shipment he characterized 
as routine 
the law requiring approval of the receiving nation went into 
effect in november 1986 the first us step to address concerns 
about toxic exports heavy fines and even jail sentences can be 
imposed for willful violations 
</TEXT>
