<TEXT>
japans trade minister told us officials 
tuesday his government plans to open transpacific hotlines to help 
american enterprises boost exports to his country a japanese 
official reported 
hiroshi mitsuzuka minister of international trade and industry 
informed commerce secretary edward mosbacher of the project said 
japanese embassy spokesman shingo yamagami 
under the plan us exporters or potential exporters would be 
invited to call in questions problems or complaints directly to 
the tokyo miti ministry overseer of the countrys global trade 
using circuits available at japanese government commercial offices 
in new york los angeles and three other us cities he said 
complaints of japanese import barriers and other red tape are a 
major source of trade friction between the two countries 
aggravated by a us trade deficit with japan last year of 52 
billion which after a modest drop is again rising 
details such as whether the hotlines would be for voice 
conversation or data exchange were not yet available the spokesman 
said there was no immediate us reaction 
japan south korea and other countries enjoying large trade 
surpluses with america are lobbying vigorously to avoid being 
targeted by the end of this month for potential retaliation under 
1988 us trade legislation 
in another development us secretary of state james baker iii 
was quoted by a japanese official as warning mitsuzuka that rising 
us protectionist pressure will increase tension between the 
united states and japan challenging the two countries to manage 
their relations more effectively in the coming years 
hideo muraoka deputy miti minister briefing japanese 
reporters added that baker was optimistic that effective and 
proper management will be possible 
three ministers of japanese prime minister noboru takeshitas 
cabinet were in washington on tuesday even though the prime 
minister plans to resign later this month because of involvement in 
an influence scandal 
besides mitsuzuka they were agriculture minister tsutomu hata 
and masahisa aoki directorgeneral of the environment protection 
agency 
officials of both governments said the visits were planned 
before takeshita announced he would step down and reflected the 
japanese decision to conduct normal government operations during 
the transition takeshita himself is on a previouslyscheduled tour 
of southeast asia 
