<TEXT>
the house banking committee on tuesday voted 
492 approval of president bushs proposal to spend 157 billion 
over 10 years to bail out the savings and loan industry from what 
has been described as the worst financial crisis since the 
depression 
the bill also would put sampl regulators under more direct 
administration control spend 75 million a year on investigating 
and prosecuting fraud at sampls and in the key reform require sampl 
owners to risk more of their own money when they make loans 
the only dissenting votes cast just before midnight after a 
14hour session were from reps joseph kennedy dmass and jim 
leach riowa kennedy said he would have preferred the bill to 
provide more housing help for poor people and antidiscrimination 
provisions leach said he wanted tougher capital standards 
the legislation requires sampl owners to risk 3 of real money 
or tangible capital for every 100 they lend double the 
requirement of the bill passed by the senate last month the 
capital would act as a buffer to absorb losses before government 
deposit insurance kicks in 
david w mullins assistant secretary of the treasury and one of 
the bush proposals architects praised the bill saying this 
committee exceeded everyones expectations despite all the 
criticism of the bush plan the plain fact is its gone through 
pretty much intact 
this is a good bill we all have reason to be proud 
said rep henry b gonzalez dtexas the committees chairman 
we will move this bill on the fast track as fast as house rules 
allow 
after the banking panel completes its report on the bill 
probably by the end of next week at least two other committees 
ways and means and judiciary will have one week to review 
sections within their jurisdiction 
then depending on how long the full house devotes to debate and 
action a joint housesenate conference committee could resolve 
differences between the two chambers and put the bill on the 
presidents desk by the july 4 recess five months after bush made 
his proposal 
the administration has endorsed the capital provisions of the 
house bill but rep claude pepper dfla chairman of the rules 
committee is objecting arguing it is unfair to take away capital 
breaks given to sampls in the early 1980s in exchange for their 
takeover of ailing institutions 
peppers committee sets the rules governing debate on the house 
floor and committee members and their aides said they expect he 
will insist the full house get the chance to amend the capital 
standards 
most of the cost of the bailout will be born by taxpayers the 
rest by the sampl industry however 50 billion of the spending in 
the next three years will be excluded from the budget deficit 
through a complicated plan for borrowing the money helping bush 
meet his no new taxes pledge 
two provisions in the house legislation not adopted by the 
senate are aimed at helping poor people obtain housing one 
offered by rep barney frank dmass and adopted 3318 requires 
the new government agency that will liquidate failed sampls the 
resolution trust corp to offer poor people and nonprofit groups 
at least a threemonth option to buy lowpriced residential 
properties owned by failed sampls 
two republicans joined the 31 democrats on the panel in passing 
the amendment the 18 republicans opposing it argued that franks 
proposal would dangerously restrict the governments ability to 
sell property from failed sampls open the government to lawsuits and 
eventually add to the taxpayer cost of the bailout 
frank however said his plan affected only 2 billion to 3 
billion of the 200 billion to 300 billion in real estate the 
government will inherit from sick institutions and argued that it 
was a modest way to channel a few of the benefits of the massive 
sampl bill to the public 
a provision offered by gonzalez and adopted last week requires 
the sampl industry through the regional federal home loan banks to 
provide 75 million a year to pay for reducedrate mortgages for 
poor people 
however the house panel on tuesday defeated a pair of 
amendments aimed at encouraging banks to do a better job of serving 
poor people and minorities 
on a 2723 vote with seven democrats joining all 20 republicans 
the panel rejected an amendment by gonzalez and kennedy that would 
have forced banks and sampls to publicly disclose federal regulators 
ratings on how well they serve poor and minorities neighborhoods 
by a 3021 vote with 10 democrats joining 20 republicans it 
voted against an amendment requiring regulators to report 
information on mortgage lending by race age and gender 
if you think for a second that discrimination doesnt exist in 
financial institutions then we are living in disney world because 
it happens every day said rep robert garcia dny 
opponents said public disclosure of ratings kept by banking 
regulators would be misinterpreted by depositors and used by civil 
rights and community groups to create mischief 
in other action tuesday the house committee 
expanded the board overseeing the resolution trust corp from 
three members to five members including housing and urban 
development secretary jack kemp and a private real estate expert 
bush had wanted a threemember board headed by treasury 
secretary nicholas brady and including attorney general dick 
thornburgh and federal reserve chairman alan greenspan 
the committee also added federal deposit insurance corp 
chairman l william seidman as a nonvoting member he likely will 
be in charge of the daytoday task of administering the cleanup 
voted 3316 to adopt an amendment by rep toby roth rwis to 
require banks and sampls with assets of more than 150 million to 
obtain independent audits of their financial condition 
defeated 2623 an amendment by rep charles schumer dny 
that would have permitted regulators to revoke special accounting 
breaks granted to acquirors of failed sampls in 1988 
</TEXT>
